{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"741cb35c-1907-4ec9-963c-c653246ba4a9","content":"This is a TUnit project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` with a path-based syntax (`/assembly/namespace/class/test`). The command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args. The filter `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches any assembly, any namespace, the `SmsNotificationTests` class, and all tests within it — so it will run `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27f20592-bf35-4521-8441-0e8cc0bff1f4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit, the test filtering uses `--treenode-filter` with a specific syntax. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so `dotnet test` might not work the same way. TUnit projects are typically run with `dotnet run` since they compile to an executable.\n\n\nThe csproj confirms this with `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, so it's definitely an MTP-based executable. With TUnit, I can use `dotnet run` with the `--treenode-filter` flag, which expects a path-like syntax of `/Namespace/Class/Test`. To filter by the `SmsNotificationTests` class specifically, I'd structure the filter accordingly.","outputTokens":619,"requestId":"5C28:2AF1D1:18CF6B:1F747E:69F55242"},"id":"c6c1dd63-ca67-457e-8056-088075678d08","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:24:32.841Z","parentId":"5ad9998b-3169-4e2f-a039-373e1cfa2566"}
